\begin_layout Subsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survival analysis is the study of time intervals.
 We are often faced with the task of predicting the time until an event
 occurs, such as biological or mechanical failure, given some historical
 data.
 Or we may have to decide whether a covariate has any effect on the expected
 survival time of an individual.
 Several properties of survival data make survival analysis unique compared
 to other temporal analyses.
 Often, some of the data is censored, and we only know the time interval
 during which an event did not occur.
 This situation is common in clinical data when a subject becomes unavailable
 for observation.
 Since the time of the event is not known, the observation is said to be
 
\emph on
right censored
\emph default
.
 Additionally, survival times generally come from skewed distributions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "clark2003survival"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In multivariate survival analysis, we may have to decide whether one or
 more covariates have an effect on the expected survival time.
 The covariates can be continuous or discrete.
 For example, in clinical data it is common to consider age, gender, and
 smoking habits as potential indicators for disease risk or life expectancy.
 The decision whether to include any of these covariates in a model is usually
 based on the results of statistical tests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cox Proportional Hazards (PH) regression model was introduced several
 decades ago by Sir David Cox 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cox1992regression"

\end_inset

.
 This model defines a 
\emph on
hazard function
\emph default
, which is the risk of an event occurring at any given time as a function
 of the observed covariates.
 When dealing with clinical data, there are many scenarios where the survival
 times are clustered.
 This can be due to geographical clustering, subjects sharing a common gene,
 or some other predisposition that cannot be observed directly.
 To account for this clustering, the 
\emph on
shared frailty model
\emph default
 was introduced 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "therneau2000modeling"

\end_inset

.
 This model makes the assumption that there exists a random variable, the
 
\emph on
frailty
\emph default
, which comprises the unobservable dependency between members of a cluster.
 Given the observed covariates and the unobservable frailty, survival times
 within a cluster are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed project is an R implementation of a shared frailty model.
 This proposal presents the motivation and strategy to develop an R package
 capable of parameter estimation, data generation, and visualization, and
 is largely an implementation of the algorithm proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gorfine2006prospective"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently, shared frailty model parameters are generally determined by a
 penalized partial likelihood method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ripatti2000estimation"

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gorfine2006prospective"

\end_inset

, an alternative algorithm is proposed that avoids several limitations of
 this approach, as well as expectation maximization (EM).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hazard function in a shared frailty model is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{ij}\left(t\right)=\omega_{i}\lambda_{0}\left(t\right)\expBetaZ
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the frailty value for family 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the unspecified baseline hazard function, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf \beta}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient vector, and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf Z_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of covariates for individual 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in family 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 comes from some distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\omega;{\bf \theta})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf \theta}$
\end_inset

 is a parameter vector.
 While only several frailty distributions have theoretical support and R
 implementations for the penalized likelihood approach, the estimation procedure
 provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gorfine2006prospective"

\end_inset

 is capable of handling any frailty distribution with finite moments.
 The implementation of a general shared frailty model will allow practitioners
 to choose the appropriate frailty distribution based on their data as opposed
 to using one of only several frailty distributions currently implemented.
 Additionally, results obtained with the proposed package can be interpreted
 with confidence, as this estimator has proved consistency and asymptotic
 normality.
\end_layout

